===Etymology===
Attested since about 1300 as {{inh|en|enm|almond}}, {{m|enm|almaund}}; from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|almande|almande, amande}}, from {{etyl|VL.|en}} {{m|la|*amendla|*amendla, amandula}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|amygdala}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ἀμυγδάλη|sc=polytonic}}, of uncertain origin. Influenced by {{m|la|amandus}} and by many French and Spanish words of Arabic origin that began with the Arabic definite article ''al-''.<ref>{{R:Etymonline}}</ref>

